The factorial of a non-negative integer n, written n factorial, is the product of all positive integers less than or equal to n. In programming, this mathematical definition translates naturally into a recursive function. The following Python implementation demonstrates the concept concisely.

def factorial(n):
    if n == 0 or n == 1:
        return 1
    return n * factorial(n - 1)

The function accepts a single parameter n. If n equals zero or one, it returns one immediately, as both zero factorial and one factorial equal one by definition. Otherwise, it returns n multiplied by the result of calling itself with n minus one. This recursive step breaks the problem into smaller subproblems until reaching the base case. For example, factorial of four evaluates as four times factorial of three, which becomes four times three times factorial of two, eventually resolving to four times three times two times one, yielding twenty-four. Recursion requires careful handling to avoid infinite loops; always ensure the base case is reachable and the input moves closer to it with each call.
